The Kaduna State Government has concluded plans to establish a Covid-19 Centre in Southern Kaduna to help curb the spread of the disease. Officials of the Kaduna State Ministry of Health visited Jema’a Local Government Area of the State to inspect suitable facilities that may be converted to Covid-19 Centre in the Area. Leader of the delegation Dr. Julius Gajere said they were in the Local Government to inspect suitable facilities that could be converted as Centre to help fight the pandemic in the region. Dr Gajere said, they have seen all the available facilities and would report to the state government their findings for final approval, adding that
when established, the Centre would service the eight local government areas of southern kaduna. The facilities visited were the Sir Patrick Ibrahim Yakowa memorial hospital Kafanchan and Godogodo Development Area Secretariat. Earlier, the Executive chairman Jema’a Local Government Hon Peter Danjuma Averik has described the decision to establish a Centre in the region to help curtail cases of covid-19 in the area as a welcome development. He said the need to have such a Centre in southern kaduna cannot be overemphasized as it would help to curtail the spread of the pandemic across the geopolitical zone through early detection and management. He promised that his council was ready to support the establishment of the Centre which he said would among other things bring development to the people of the Area.